    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="142"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d142">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">842.20 Defense/12–3044</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Ambassador in Canada</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Canadian Secretary of State for External
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mackenzie King</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="4" xml:id="d142fn4">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Ambassador in Canada in his letter of December 30, 1944, not printed.
                        The acceptance by the Embassy of the Canadian proposals was made on basis of
                        telephone instructions from the Department of State.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 262</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ottawa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-30">December 30,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note No. 141 of December 28, 1944, concerning the acquisition by the
                    Canadian <pb facs="0225" n="213" xml:id="pg_213"/> Government of land required
                    by the United States for the purpose of carrying out defence projects in
                    Canada.</p>
                <p>In reply I am pleased to be able to inform you that the proposals for the purpose
                    of solving the problem of acquisition of land for United States defence
                    projects, which are set forth in the memorandum enclosed with your note, are
                    acceptable to my Government.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ray Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
